\begin_layout Standard
Consider solving the system 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
y=\cos(x)\\
y=x
\end{cases}.
\]

\end_inset

One way to do so is by the method of substitution.
 If we substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\cos x$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\cos x$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos x=x$
\end_inset

.
 The solutions of the system coincide exactly with the fixed points of the
 cosine function, for any solution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos x=x$
\end_inset

 is a value 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 that is fixed by the cosine.
 Since systems of two equations in two unknowns can be solved, at least
 approximately, by graphing, this suggests that we might take a look at
 the graph of the system in order to learn more about what is happening
 during iteration.
\end_layout

