\begin_layout Standard
What if we start with a number other than 0? Using figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:cosine-fixed-point"

\end_inset

, you should be able to convince yourself that convergence to the point
 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.7390851332\ldots,0.7390851332\ldots)$
\end_inset

 is assured for any initial value between 0 and 1.
 Try it.
 Start anywhere on the line 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x$
\end_inset

.
 Proceed vertically to the graph of 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\cos(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then horizontally to the line 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x$
\end_inset

.
 And repeat.
 You should find that the path of the web diagram always tends toward the
 intersection of the graphs.
 Now consider starting with any real number, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 The cosine of any real number is a number in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[-1,1]$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(r)\in[-1,1]$
\end_inset

.
 And the cosine of any number in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[-1,1]$
\end_inset

 is a number in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(\cos(r))\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 That is, the second iteration is in the interval from 0 to 1.
 So after only two iterations, any initial value will become a value between
 0 and 1.
 And our web diagram implies that further iteration will lead to the fixed
 point.
 So, regardless of the initial value, iteration leads to the fixed point.
 And the preceding argument forms the seed for a proof of this fact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Not all functions are so well behaved, however.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is a fixed point of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 However, iteration starting with any number other than 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 does not lead to this fixed point.
 If we start with any number greater than 1 and square it, it becomes greater.
 And if we square the result, it becomes greater still.
 And squaring again only increases the value, without bound.
 Hence, iteration starting with any value greater than 1 (or less than 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

) does not lead to convergence to the fixed point 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Nor does iteration starting with any number of magnitude less than 1.
