\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:contractive"

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)$
\end_inset

 is differentiable on 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|h'(x)|<1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in(a,b)$
\end_inset

, then whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2}\in(a,b)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $|h(x_{2})-h(x_{1})|<|x_{2}-x_{1}|$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2}\in(a,b)$
\end_inset

 and, without loss of generality, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}>x_{1}$
\end_inset

 so that we may properly refer to the interval from 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)$
\end_inset

 is continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $[x_{1},x_{2}]$
\end_inset

 and differentiable on 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1},x_{2})$
\end_inset

, the mean value theorem gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in(x_{1},x_{2})\subseteq(a,b)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $h'(c)=\left|\frac{h(x_{2})-h(x_{1})}{x_{2}-x_{1}}\right|$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $h'(c)<1$
\end_inset

 by assumption, so 
\begin_inset Formula $h'(c)=\left|\frac{h(x_{2})-h(x_{1})}{x_{2}-x_{1}}\right|<1$
\end_inset

, from which we immediately conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $|h(x_{2})-h(x_{1})|<|x_{2}-x_{1}|$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, a function whose derivative has magnitude less than 1 can only
 cross the line 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x$
\end_inset

 one time.
 Once it has crossed, it can never 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

catch up
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 because that would require a slope greater than 1, the slope of the line
 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:uniquenessOfFixedPoint"

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)$
\end_inset

 is continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

, differentiable on 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|h'(x)|<1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in(a,b)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $h([a,b])\subseteq[a,b]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 has a unique fixed point in 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
If 
\begin_inset Formula $h(a)=a$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $h(b)=b$
\end_inset

, we have proved existence, so suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $h(a)\neq a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h(b)\neq b$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $h([a,b])\subseteq[a,b]$
\end_inset

 it must be the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $h(a)>a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h(b)<b$
\end_inset

.
 It immediately follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $h(a)-a>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h(b)-b<0$
\end_inset

.
 Since the auxiliary function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=h(x)-x$
\end_inset

 is continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

, the Intermediate Value Theorem guarantees the existence of 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in(a,b)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(c)=0$
\end_inset

.
 By substitution, 
\begin_inset Formula $h(c)-c=0$
\end_inset

, implying 
\begin_inset Formula $h(c)=c$
\end_inset

,  so 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is a fixed point of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 The existence of a fixed point is established.
 Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}\in[a,b]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}\in[a,b]$
\end_inset

 are distinct fixed points of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{h(c_{1})-h(c_{2})}{c_{1}-c_{2}}=\frac{c_{1}-c_{2}}{c_{1}-c_{2}}=1.
\]

\end_inset

 By the mean value theorem, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{3}$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $h'(c_{3})=1$
\end_inset

, contradicting the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $|h'(x)|<1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in(a,b)$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, it is impossible that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}$
\end_inset

 are distinct.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, we can reasonably expect that when the derivative at a fixed point
 has magnitude less than 1, iteration is a viable method for approximating
 (finding) the fixed point, but when the derivative at a fixed point has
 magnitude greater than 1, iteration is not a viable method of approximating
 the fixed point.
 We must be careful, though, not to take this rule of thumb as absolute.
 It only applies to so-called well-behaved functions.
 In this case, that the function has a continuous first derivative in the
 neighborhood of the fixed point is well-behaved enough.
 The following theorem establishes that fixed point iteration will converge
 in a neighborhood of a fixed point if the magnitude of the function's derivativ
e is less than 1 there.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:fixedPointConvergence"

\end_inset

(Fixed Point Convergence Theorem) 
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Theorem ! Fixed Point Convergence
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Given a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 with continuous first derivative and fixed point 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $|f'(\hat{x})|<1$
\end_inset

 then there exists a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 in which fixed point iteration converges to the fixed point for any initial
 value in the neighborhood.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
By continuity, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|f'(x)|<1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in(\hat{x}-\varepsilon,\hat{x}+\varepsilon)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\delta<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle M=\max_{x\in[\hat{x}-\delta,\hat{x}+\delta]}|f'(x)|}$
\end_inset

.
 Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a particular but arbitrary value in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\hat{x}-\delta,\hat{x}+\delta)$
\end_inset

.
 As in proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:contractive"

\end_inset

, the Mean Value Theorem is applied.
 This time, we are guaranteed 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle c\in(\hat{x}-\delta,\hat{x}+\delta)}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(c)=\frac{f(\hat{x})-f(x_{0})}{\hat{x}-x_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $|f'(c)|\leq M$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $|f(\hat{x})-f(x_{0})|\leq M|\hat{x}-x_{0}|$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 is a fixed point, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\hat{x})=\hat{x}$
\end_inset

, from which it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $|\hat{x}-f(x_{0})|\leq M|\hat{x}-x_{0}|$
\end_inset

.
 Now we define 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{k}=f(x_{k-1})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq1$
\end_inset

 and prove by induction that 
\begin_inset Formula $|\hat{x}-x_{k}|\leq M^{k}|\hat{x}-x_{0}|$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=f(x_{0})$
\end_inset

, we have already shown 
\begin_inset Formula $|\hat{x}-x_{1}|\leq M|\hat{x}-x_{0}|$
\end_inset

, so the claim is true when 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

.
 Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $|\hat{x}-x_{k}|\leq M^{k}|\hat{x}-x_{0}|$
\end_inset

 for some particular but arbitrary value 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $|\hat{x}-x_{k}|\leq M^{k}|\hat{x}-x_{0}|$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{k}\in(\hat{x}-\delta,\hat{x}+\delta)$
\end_inset

 so we apply the Mean Value Theorem as before and conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $|\hat{x}-f(x_{k})|\leq M|\hat{x}-x_{k}|$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{k+1}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{k})$
\end_inset

 and using the inductive hypothesis, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $|\hat{x}-x_{k+1}|\leq M\cdot M^{k}|\hat{x}-x_{0}|=M^{k+1}|\hat{x}-x_{0}|$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq|\hat{x}-x_{k}|\leq M^{k}|\hat{x}-x_{0}|$
\end_inset

.
 Of course 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \lim_{k\to\infty}0=0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \lim_{k\to\infty}M^{k}|\hat{x}-x_{0}|=0}$
\end_inset

, so by the squeeze theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \lim_{k\to\infty}|\hat{x}-x_{k}|=0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As suggested earlier, we should not expect fixed point iteration to converge
 when the derivative at a fixed point has magnitude greater than one.
 In fact, more or less the opposite happens.
 There is a neighborhood of the fixed point in which fixed point iteration
 is guaranteed to escape the neighborhood for any initial value in the neighborh
ood not equal to the fixed point itself.
 Given that fact, it is tempting to think that perhaps the Fixed Point Convergen
ce Theorem could be strengthened to a bi-directional implication, an if-and-only
-if claim.
 And it 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

almost
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can.
 What can be said here has direct parallels to the ratio test for series.
 Recall, for any sequence of real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0},a_{1},a_{2},\ldots$
\end_inset

, the limit 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle L=\lim_{k\to\infty}\left|\frac{a_{k+1}}{a_{k}}\right|}$
\end_inset

 helps determine the convergence of 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^{\infty}a_{k}}$
\end_inset

 in the following way:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $L<1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^{\infty}a_{k}}$
\end_inset

 converges (absolutely).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $L>1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^{\infty}a_{k}}$
\end_inset

 diverges.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $L=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^{\infty}a_{k}}$
\end_inset

 may converge (absolutely or conditionally) or may diverge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Analogously, for any function 
