\begin_layout Standard
When successful, fixed point iteration finds solutions of an equation of
 the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x$
\end_inset

.
 A root finding problem requires the solution of an equation of the form
 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=0$
\end_inset

.
 However, the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x$
\end_inset

 has exactly the same solutions as the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)-x=0$
\end_inset

, so finding fixed points of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to finding roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=f(x)-x$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, we can rephrase the example of finding fixed points of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\frac{1}{8}x^{3}-x^{2}+2x+1$
\end_inset

 as the problem of finding roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=f(x)-x=\frac{1}{8}x^{3}-x^{2}+x+1$
\end_inset

.
 But it is the opposite problem that is much more common.
 We have the question of finding the roots of a function and need to rephrase
 it in terms of a fixed point problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we want the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=-x^{3}+5x^{2}-4x-6$
\end_inset

.
 We can rephrase the question of solving 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=0$
\end_inset

 as the problem of finding the fixed points of many different functions!
 But you will have to ignore some sage advice of your algebra teacher to
 derive them! The key is to use algebra to rewrite the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $-x^{3}+5x^{2}-4x-6=0$
\end_inset

 as an equation of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $x=f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 The simplest way is to add 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to both sides of the equation.
 This manipulation and several others are shown in the following list.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $-x^{3}+5x^{2}-4x-6=0\Rightarrow-x^{3}+5x^{2}-3x-6=x$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $-x^{3}+5x^{2}-4x-6=0\Rightarrow-x^{3}+5x^{2}-6=4x\Rightarrow\frac{-x^{3}+5x^{2}-6}{4}=x$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $-x^{3}+5x^{2}-4x-6=0\Rightarrow-x^{3}-4x-6=-5x^{2}\Rightarrow\frac{x^{3}+4x+6}{5}=x^{2}\Rightarrow\pm\sqrt{\frac{x^{3}+4x+6}{5}}=x$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $-x^{3}+5x^{2}-4x-6=0\Rightarrow5x^{2}-4x-6=x^{3}\Rightarrow\sqrt[3]{5x^{2}-4x-6}=x$
\end_inset


\end_layout

